Oxygen and hydrogen are super clean, producing water vapor and a plume that's barely discernible to our eyes. The SRBs, by contrast, churn out all sorts of nasties, including aluminum oxide, black carbon, CO2, and hydrogen chloride. (3 of 3)

That's because the RS-25s burn oxygen and hydrogen, while the solid rocket boosters burn a bunch of things, including ammonium perchlorate, salt from perchloric acid, and polybutadiene acrylonitrile (PBAN). (2 of 3)

I don't know if today's cryogenic loading caused the loosening of the nuts, but it crossed my mind as a possibility. (4 of 4)

Components attached to the tank, like ducts, vent lines, and brackets, need to compensate for this sudden contraction. To achieve this, NASA uses connectors with accordion-like bellows, slotted joints, telescoping sections, and ball joint hinges. (3 of 4)
The 130-foot-tall (40-meter-tall) hydrogen tank shrinks about 6 inches (152 mm) in length and about 1 inch (25.4 mm) in diameter when filled with the cryogenic liquid. (2 of 4)
During tanking of SLS, the sudden influx of supercool hydrogen causes significant changes to the rocket’s physical structure. (1 of 4)

Should RTV come off SLS during launch, this debris would most likely strike the Launch Vehicle Stage Adapter. The inner areas of the boosters also at potential risk, said Sarafin.

Hurricane Nicole caused a 10-foot section of caulk-like RTV material to come off Orion. Sarafin said there's a "nonzero" chance that additional RTV will come off during launch and strike the rocket downstream, but risk is acceptable.
